      <div
        class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-headings:font-semibold prose-headings:tracking-tight prose-a:text-brand-600"
      >
        <h2>Common takeoff mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Counting from the wrong drawing revision.</strong> Always confirm you have the current
            addendum before starting. Superseded sheets can differ significantly from what gets built.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Skipping the spec book.</strong> Material upgrade requirements, testing costs, and
            coordination requirements live in the spec, not the drawings. Missing them costs money in
            the field.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Scaling from reduced drawings.</strong> If the drawings have been reduced for printing,
            the scale bar is wrong. Either work from full-size prints or use the drawing's own scale bar
            — never assume the printed page is full size.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Pricing from plan symbols instead of schedules.</strong> Symbols can be missed or
            added without updating the plan. The equipment schedule is the authoritative count.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Leaving scope gaps unresolved.</strong> If you can't tell whether an item is in your
            scope, ask the GC in writing before bid day. Assumptions that go unchecked become disputes
            once the contract is signed.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          A takeoff takes longer than skipping it, but a missed quantity on a fixed-price contract
          comes out of your margin. The discipline of working through the drawings methodically —
          sheet by sheet, room by room, schedule by schedule — is what separates bids that hold
          their margins from bids that erode the moment construction starts.
        </p>

        <p>
          Once the job is won and the contract signed, the same line-item structure that organized
          your bid becomes the{' '}
          <a href="/blog/schedule-of-values-guide/">schedule of values</a> for your{' '}
          <a href="/features/pay-applications/">pay applications</a> — so accurate quantities at bid time
          pay off through the entire life of the job.
        </p>
      </div>

